{"version":"1.2","person":{"datePublished":"2023-09-06","name":"William FitzNeale","nameForms":[{"lang":"und","fullText":"William FitzNeale","parts":[{"type":"http://gedcomx.org/Given","value":"William"},{"type":"http://gedcomx.org/Surname","value":"FitzNeale"}],"order":"EUROTYPIC"}],"alternateName":"William of Ely","gender":"Male","lifespan":"1150–Male","fullLifespan":"1150–","birthDate":"+1150","birthPlace":{"address":"Buckinghamshire, England","geo":{"latitude":51.76274,"longitude":-0.65918,"@type":"GeoCoordinates"},"@type":"Place"},"userCertifiedLifeSummary":"From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia\nhttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_of_Ely\n\nWilliam of Ely was an English churchman and the fifth Lord High Treasurer of England. He was a relative of Richard FitzNeal and supposed descendant of Nigel, Bishop of Ely, both previous Lord High Treasurers. He was appointed a Canon of St. Paul's just before being made Lord High Treasurer in 1196. He added the position of Archdeacon of Cleveland in 1201 and Prebendary of Leighton Buzzard in 1207.[1]\n\nA story about William of Ely tells of his attempted escape from England during a time when he had fallen from favour with the King; he was disguised as a commoner but was stopped when he proved unable to respond to a simple question posed to him in English (illustrating the dominance of the French language among nobles and clergymen at the time).[2] \n\nList of Lord High Treasurers:\nhttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Lord_High_Treasurers_of_England_and_Great_Britain\n\nReferences:\nPainter, Sydney (1979). The Reign of King John. Ayer Publishing. pp. 66–67.\nWalter, Henriette (1994). Aventure des langues en Occident : leur origine, leur histoire, leur géographie. Paris: Laffont. p. 379.","events":[{"name":"Birth","sources":"0","year":"1150","date":"1150","place":"Buckinghamshire, England"},{"name":"Birth of Child","sources":"0","year":"1190","date":"1190","place":"Borstall,Buckinghamshire, England","age":"40","id":"LRW6